@node Interest profile
@section Interest profile

@vindex elfeed-ai-interest-profile
The user option @code{elfeed-ai-interest-profile} is a free-form string @*
describing your interests in natural language.  This string is included @*
verbatim in every AI scoring prompt, so the more specific and @*
descriptive it is, the better the model can judge relevance. @*

The value accepts two forms: @*

@itemize
@item
An inline string (e.g., @code{"AI safety, Emacs, functional programming"}). @*
@item
A file path pointing to a readable file whose contents are used as @*
the profile text.  This is useful for lengthy, detailed profiles @*
that would be unwieldy as a Lisp string. @*
@end itemize

When the value is empty, scoring is skipped entirely---no API calls @*
are made.  The default value is an empty string. @*

The type is @code{(choice string file)}. @*

@node Scoring behavior
@section Scoring behavior

@vindex elfeed-ai-auto-score
@vindex elfeed-ai-generate-summary
@vindex elfeed-ai-summary-prompt
@vindex elfeed-ai-relevance-threshold
@vindex elfeed-ai-score-unscored-days
@vindex elfeed-ai-max-content-length
The user option @code{elfeed-ai-auto-score} controls whether new entries are @*
automatically queued for scoring as they arrive via @*
@code{elfeed-new-entry-hook}.  The default is @code{t}.  Set it to @code{nil} if you @*
prefer to score entries manually with @code{elfeed-ai-score} (@ref{Scoring entries, , Scoring @*
entries}). @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-generate-summary} controls whether the AI @*
produces a short summary alongside the relevance score.  The default @*
is @code{t}.  Summaries are displayed in the show buffer above the original @*
content.  Setting this to @code{nil} reduces token usage per entry, which @*
is useful if you are on a tight budget (@ref{Budget}) or only care about @*
the score. @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-summary-prompt} is the instruction appended @*
to the scoring prompt that describes what the summary should contain. @*
It is only used when @code{elfeed-ai-generate-summary} is non-nil.  The @*
text is inserted after the request for a @code{"summary"} JSON key, so it @*
should describe the desired content and length of the summary rather @*
than repeating structural instructions.  The default value is @*
@code{"a 1-3 sentence summary of the content"}.  You might change this to, @*
for example, @code{"a one-paragraph explanation of why this is relevant to
the user's interests"} to get more targeted summaries.  The type is @*
@code{string}. @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-relevance-threshold} sets the minimum AI @*
score (a float between 0.0 and 1.0) for an entry to receive the @*
@code{elfeed-ai-score-tag} tag.  When @code{nil} (the default), no tags are @*
added and entries are scored only---you can still sort by score and @*
view summaries.  When set to a number, entries scoring at or above the @*
threshold are tagged, and entries scoring below it are not tagged.  In @*
both cases, the score is stored in @code{elfeed-meta}. @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-score-unscored-days} specifies the default @*
number of days to look back when invoking @code{elfeed-ai-score-unscored} @*
(@ref{Scoring unscored entries}).  The default is @code{7}.  With a prefix @*
argument, the command prompts for a custom number of days, ignoring @*
this option. @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-max-content-length} sets the maximum number @*
of characters of entry content sent to the AI@.  Longer content is @*
truncated.  The default is @code{4000}.  Increasing this value gives the @*
model more context for judging relevance, at the cost of higher token @*
usage. @*

@node Budget
@section Budget

@vindex elfeed-ai-daily-budget
@vindex elfeed-ai-budget-reset-hour
@vindex elfeed-ai-budget-file
The user option @code{elfeed-ai-daily-budget} caps daily API usage.  Its @*
value is a cons cell of the form @code{(TYPE . LIMIT)}, where TYPE is @*
either @code{tokens} or @code{dollars}. @*

In @code{tokens} mode, usage is estimated heuristically at one token per @*
four characters.  This provides a rough safeguard without requiring @*
external cost-tracking infrastructure. @*

In @code{dollars} mode, actual cost is computed via @code{gptel-plus-compute-cost} @*
from the @samp{gptel-plus} package.  If @samp{gptel-plus} is not available, the @*
budget is not enforced and a warning is logged at startup.  Dollar @*
mode also displays the cost of the last 100 scored entries in the @*
transient menu heading (@ref{Transient menu}), helping you calibrate your @*
budget. @*

The default value is @code{(dollars . 1.00)}.  The type is @*
@code{(choice (cons tokens integer) (cons dollars number))}. @*

The obsolete variable @code{elfeed-ai-daily-token-budget} is superseded by @*
@code{elfeed-ai-daily-budget} as of version 0.2.0. @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-budget-reset-hour} specifies the hour @*
(0--23) at which the daily budget resets.  If the current hour is @*
before this value, yesterday's date is used for budget tracking, so a @*
late-night scoring session counts against the previous day's budget. @*
The default is @code{0} (midnight). @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-budget-file} specifies the file used to @*
persist daily usage data across Emacs sessions.  The default is @*
@samp{elfeed-ai-budget.eld} in @code{user-emacs-directory}. @*

@node Tags
@section Tags

@vindex elfeed-ai-score-tag
The user option @code{elfeed-ai-score-tag} is the tag added to entries whose @*
AI score meets or exceeds @code{elfeed-ai-relevance-threshold} @*
(@ref{Scoring behavior}).  This tag is only used when @*
@code{elfeed-ai-relevance-threshold} is non-nil.  The default is @*
@code{elfeed-ai}.  You can change this to any symbol, then use it in elfeed @*
search filters (e.g., @samp{+my-custom-tag +unread}). @*

@node AI backend and model
@section AI backend and model

@vindex elfeed-ai-backend
@vindex elfeed-ai-model
The user option @code{elfeed-ai-backend} specifies the gptel backend name @*
for AI scoring (e.g., @code{"Gemini"} or @code{"Claude"}).  When @code{nil}, the @*
backend is inferred: if @code{elfeed-ai-model} is set, @samp{elfeed-ai} searches @*
@code{gptel--known-backends} for a backend that provides that model; if no @*
match is found, it falls back to @code{gptel-backend}.  The default is @*
@code{nil}. @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-model} specifies the gptel model for AI @*
scoring (e.g., @code{claude-sonnet-4-5-20250514}).  When @code{nil}, defaults to @*
@code{gptel-model}.  The default is @code{nil}. @*

Both options can be adjusted interactively via the transient menu @*
(@ref{Transient menu}).  Setting these options allows you to use a @*
different (potentially cheaper or faster) model for feed scoring than @*
your default gptel model. @*

@node Display
@section Display

@vindex elfeed-ai-sort-by-score
@vindex elfeed-ai-score-high-threshold
@vindex elfeed-ai-score-low-threshold
The user option @code{elfeed-ai-sort-by-score} controls whether the search @*
buffer is sorted by AI score (highest first) when @code{elfeed-ai-mode} is @*
active.  Unscored entries are sorted after scored ones; entries with @*
equal scores are sorted by date (newest first).  The default is @code{t}. @*
You can toggle sorting at any time with @code{elfeed-ai-toggle-sort} @*
(@ref{Toggling sort order}). @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-score-high-threshold} sets the minimum @*
score for the high-score face.  Scores at or above this value are @*
rendered with @code{elfeed-ai-score-high-face} (@ref{Faces}).  The default is @*
@code{0.7}. @*

The user option @code{elfeed-ai-score-low-threshold} sets the maximum score @*
for the low-score face.  Scores at or below this value are rendered @*
with @code{elfeed-ai-score-low-face} (@ref{Faces}).  The default is @code{0.3}. @*

Scores between the two thresholds use the default @*
@code{elfeed-ai-score-face}. @*

